{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564897"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17164"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17164"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.1,0.41,0.01,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68852"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54309"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4517"},{"type":"tags","id":"10779"},{"type":"tags","id":"10781"},{"type":"tags","id":"11159"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32250"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68852"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit. She reports a positive home pregnancy test two days ago. Her last menstrual period was six weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. She is a primary school teacher and lives with her partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is interested in having prenatal screening and asks specifically about non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT), as her friend recently had this test.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important limitation of NIPT to discuss with this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Need for confirmatory testing","False positive rate","Cannot detect structural anomalies","Turnaround time for results","Cost of the test"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario highlights the importance of appropriate counselling regarding prenatal screening options. While NIPT is an excellent screening test for common chromosomal abnormalities, it has important limitations that must be discussed with patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECannot detect structural anomalies\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant limitation of NIPT to discuss. While NIPT has excellent sensitivity and specificity for detecting common chromosomal abnormalities like trisomy 21, 18, and 13, it cannot detect structural or anatomical abnormalities such as neural tube defects, cardiac defects, or limb abnormalities. This is why a first trimester ultrasound remains essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecost of the test\u003C/strong\u003E, while significant as it is not covered by Medicare, is not the most important limitation from a clinical perspective. The cost should be discussed but does not impact the test\u0027s clinical utility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efalse positive rate\u003C/strong\u003E of NIPT is actually very low (less than 1% for most conditions), making it one of the most specific screening tests available for chromosomal abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eturnaround time for results\u003C/strong\u003E is typically 3-5 working days, which is reasonable for a screening test and allows time for decision-making about further testing if required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eneed for confirmatory testing\u003C/strong\u003E with diagnostic procedures like amniocentesis after a positive NIPT result is important but affects a very small proportion of women who receive a high-risk result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen counselling patients about prenatal screening, it\u0027s essential to emphasise that no single test can detect all possible fetal abnormalities, and a combination of screening modalities including NIPT and ultrasound provides the most comprehensive assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) has high sensitivity and specificity for common chromosomal abnormalities but cannot detect structural anomalies.","First trimester ultrasound remains essential for detecting structural abnormalities and establishing accurate dating.","Counselling for prenatal screening should include discussion of both the capabilities and limitations of each test."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Fetal anomalies: clinical guideline [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): RANZCOG; 2016 [cited 2024 Dec 10]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Fetal-Anomalies-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54309"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17164"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54309"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T16:26:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T16:28:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9854"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68852"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","i